.TH "WEBTRANSPORT.CONGESTIONCONTROL" "3JS" "February 24, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
WebTransport.congestionControl \- WebTransport: congestionControl
property
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Secure context:\f[R] This feature is available only in secure
contexts (HTTPS).
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]congestionControl\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]WebTransport\f[R] interface indicates the application\(cqs
preference for either high throughput or low\-latency when sending data.
.PP
The value is set in the \f[CR]WebTransport()\f[R] constructor options.
.SH VALUE
A string with one of the following values:
.TP
\f[B]default\f[R]
The default congestion control tuning for the transport.
This is the default.
.TP
\f[B]throughput\f[R]
The application prefers congestion control to be tuned for throughput.
.TP
\f[B]low\-latency\f[R]
The application prefers congestion control to be tuned for low\-latency.
.SH EXAMPLES
This example shows how to get the \f[CR]congestionControl\f[R]
preference.
As this is not explicitly set in the constructor, the result is
\f[CR]default\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] url = \(dqhttps://example.com:4999/wt\(dq;
\f[B]const\f[R] transport = \f[B]new\f[R] WebTransport(url);
console.log(transport.congestionControl); \f[I]// default\f[R]
.EE
